💻 No one likes giving the PTE every 2 years. If you’ve studied in an English speaking University for the last couple of years, your English has only gotten better, not worse. Having said that, we’ve introduced a PTE Academic Speaking masterclass wherein we emphasise on how to master the PTE Speaking module, avoid most common mistakes, and maximise your scoring ability.
 
📑 The Workshop takes place twice a month, on the 2nd and 4th Saturdays of the month, and there are six seats (we avoid overcrowding for better understanding- both ways).

📍Location: 85 Queen Street, Melbourne VIC 3000

🕥 Time: 10:30am 

💺 DM @elmasteryy now to book your FREE seat

🎖To qualify for the Free Masterclass:

1️⃣ The candidate should be able to provide their previous scoresheet (could be any English language test, not necessarily PTE).

2️⃣ Be able to commit at least 30 mins everyday for the next 2 weeks to practice the strategies taught in the workshop.
.
.

One of the most daunting things to happen on PTE/IELTS test day is being asked to write an essay on a topic that is not of your interest, or even worse, a topic that you have no idea about. In this video, I will be discussing how such occurrences are normal, and can be avoided with a bit of strategising. 

Good luck!
.

An important preposition in English. “On” is also used with some verbs such as:
Get on = to have a good relationship
Take on = to accept extra work.
Build on = to use your success to go further 
Decide on = to choose
Hold on = to wait
Try on = to try clothes to see if they fit
Go on = to continue
Etc.

important! 

Repost: @theenglishacademy_sg 

Here are a few words that are often mispronounced
 
Almonds = aw-muhndz
(You can imagine the "L" is silent)

Sword = Sord
(You can imagine the "W" is silent)

Divorce = duh-vors
(Not "die"vorse - it may be the end of a
relationship but you won't "die")

Lettuce = let-uhs
(As is "let us" use proper pronunciation)
